The Observations and Measurements models, following the OGC Best Practice document OGC 05-087r4

Harmonized version of SWE Common basic type library, as at conclusion of OWS-4

A model for sampling features. These feature-types are typically associated with making observations at locations that are considered in some way to be representative of a domain feature. Sampling features embody a sampling strategy that is suitable for the observation procedure and the observed property. Hence, sampling features are artefacts of the observation process rather than the inherent domain semantics. Similar sampling strategies are used across a wide range of application domains so a common sampling features schema may be described. Instances of sampling features may act as the proximate feature-of-interest for observations [O&M], particularly early in the value-adding chain.
Documented in OGC 07-002

EA-notes: Classes derived from Observation may override the type of the "result" property with an appropriate type.
The Observation feature supports an event-centric or user-centric view. The "observation" description is a map of all of the properties associated with a particular information capture event, including its result.
This contrasts with the Sensor feature, which provides a process-centric viewpoint. The "sensor system" description is effectively a map of of the properties of all potential information capture events _except_ the results.
The procedureTime is modelled as a generalized TimeObject. It will often be a geometric primitive, such as an instant or period.
The samplingTime is modelled as a generalized TimeObject. It will often be a geometric primitive, such as an instant or period.

The procedure that is the target of this association will often not be observation-instance specific, but rather a description of a generic procedure, instrument, etc. However, if it is necessary to record instance-specific details, parameters, inputs, etc, then a specific procedure-instance or procedure-event may be used. Alternatively, event-specific parameters (e.g. calibrations) may be recorded in the eventParameter property on the Observation instance.
The SamplingFeature class is defined primarily by a set of [0..*] relatedObservation associations.

The procedure that is the target of this association will usually be a description of a generic procedure, activity, instrument, etc. However, if it is necessary to record event-specific details, parameters, inputs, calibrations, etc, then either (i) eventParameter(s) may be used, or (ii) a specific procedure-instance may be used. For example, a CategoryObservation event will use a classification-procedure that may depend on more primitive observations - e.g. a set of prior measurements. As part of the description of the procedure it may be useful to be able to record these sources or inputs. It is preferable to partition these considerations with the "Procedure" rather than promoting special properties ("inputs", "source") up to the Observation class. This is consistent with some mission-specific parameters being associated with the sensor, as is done in SensorML. However, the most appropriate partioning of the generic (static) and instance specific (dynamic) information between the Observation feature and the Procedure/Sensor is to some extent arbitrary.
The Procedure must be commensurate with the Phenomenon being observed. The phenomenon-definition is treated as a first-class property of observation in order to support discovery and data fusion.

In many applications a specimen preparation procedure is applied to the material prior to its use in an observation. This may be recorded as part of the analytical procedure, or may be associated with the specimen. The processingDetails property supports the latter pattern.

A model for sampling features. These feature-types are typically associated with making observations at locations that are considered in some way to be representative of a domain feature. Sampling features embody a sampling strategy that is suitable for the observation procedure and the observed property. Hence, sampling features are artefacts of the observation process rather than the inherent domain semantics. Similar sampling strategies are used across a wide range of application domains so a common sampling features schema may be described. Instances of sampling features may act as the proximate feature-of-interest for observations [O&M], particularly early in the value-adding chain.
Documented in OGC 07-002

A hierarchy of sampling feature types may be organized on the basis of the dimensionality of their extent (Figure 4). A Station samples the world at a point, a Profile along a curve, a SurfaceOfInterest on a surface, and a SolidOfInterest in a solid region. As well as the generic soft-typed property inherited from SamplingFeature, extensive sampling features may carry properties whose values vary over the extent of the feature, which is described as a coverage [ISO 19123].Along a curve this is conventionally a propertyLog; on a surface it is designated propertyMap; in a solid it is a propertyFill. An extensive sampling feature may be sub-sampled in various ways. Thus, the shape of a sampling feature may describe the extent of a sampling domain, while not specifying the elements of the domain of a discrete coverage representation of the variation of a property within the sampling feature. It is nevertheless useful to have the description of the sampling feature and its shape as a basis for the description of the domain decomposition. Example: Logs of different properties along a well or borehole may use different intervals, and sub-samples may be either instantaneous or averaged in some way over an interval. The position of the samples may be conveniently described in terms of offsets in a linear coordinate reference system that is defined by the shape of the borehole axis.

A Specimen (Figure 5) is a physical sample, usually obtained for observation carried out ex situ, often in a laboratory. A specimen is characterized by having a currentLocation (e.g. its storage location) and an indication of its currentSize (e.g. mass), and its gross materialClass (e.g. soil, water, rock, tissue, etc).

0-D observation site Example: A 뱒tation is essentially an identifiable locality where a sensor system or procedure may be deployed and an observation made. In the context of the observation model, it connotes the 뱖orld in the vicinity of the station, so the observed properties relate to the physical medium at the station, and not to an artefact such as a mooring, benchmark, monument, well, etc.
Required if position CRS is 2D; DirectPosition in this case will be a 1D coordinate in a 1D CRS (i.e. a datum and scale)

Sampling features are frequently related to each other, as parts of networks, through sub-sampling, etc. This is supported by the relatedSamplingFeature association with a generic SamplingFeatureRelation association class, which carries a source, target and role.

The SamplingFeature class is defined primarily by a set of [0..*] relatedObservation associations. The SamplingFeature has a matching set of intrinsic (soft-typed) property attributes, such that the value of each property corresponds with the result of the related Observation.
Generic property; its value is provided by a relatedObservation

UML:Constraint.name: property.propertyType must match one or more relatedObservation.observedProperty

UML:TaggedValue.value: A common requirement for sampling features is an indication of the SurveyProcedure that provides the surveyDetails related to determination of its location and shape.

A sampling feature must be associated with one or more other features through an association role sampledFeature. This association records the intention of the sample design. The target of this association will often be a domain feature.
Examples: a sounding typically samples a water- or atmospheric-column; a well samples an aquifer; a tissue specimen samples a part of an organism
Optional pointer to the domain feature that the specimen samples

A Specimen (Figure 5) is a physical sample, usually obtained for observation carried out ex situ, often in a laboratory. A specimen is characterized by having a currentLocation (e.g. its storage location) and an indication of its currentSize (e.g. mass), and its gross materialClass (e.g. soil, water, rock, tissue, etc).
A LocatedSpecimen is a specialization of Specimen that adds information about the sampling- location, time and method.
Maybe need a more specialized SamplingProcedure hierarchy (derived from ProcedureType)

A Specimen is some physical material sampled from a specified location, typically associated with a Site, such as a Station, a location or interval within a Section, or a location or extent from a DescriptionExtent
Current location of specimen, e.g. storage location
